2. Install the EPEL repository on your system by running the following command:

   ```
   sudo yum install epel-release
   ```

3. Install Nginx web server and PHP along with some required dependencies by running the following command:

   ```
   sudo yum install nginx php-fpm php-cli php-gd php-mbstring php-xml php-zip unzip
   ```

4. Download the latest Filestash package from the official website. You can use the following command to download the package:

   ```
   wget https://github.com/mickael-kerjean/filestash/releases/download/v0.17.2/filestash-v0.17.2.zip
   ```

5. Unzip the downloaded package by running the following command:

   ```
   unzip filestash-v0.17.2.zip
   ```

6. Move the unzipped files to your Nginx root web directory by running the following command:

   ```
   sudo mv filestash-v0.17.2 /usr/share/nginx/html/filestash
   ```

7. Create a new Nginx server block file for Filestash by running the following command:

   ```
   sudo vi /etc/nginx/conf.d/filestash.conf
   ```

8. Copy and paste the following configuration into the file and save it:

   ```
   server {
       listen       80;
       server_name  your_domain_name.com;
       root         /usr/share/nginx/html/filestash;

       location / {
           try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
           index index.php;
       }

       location ~ \.php$ {
           fastcgi_pass   unix:/var/run/php-fpm/php-fpm.sock;
           fastcgi_index  index.php;
           fastcgi_param  SCRIPT_FILENAME   $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
           include        fastcgi_params;
       }

       location ~ /\.ht {
           deny  all;
       }
   }
   ```

   Note: Replace your_domain_name.com with your actual domain name.

9. Restart the Nginx web server by running the following command:

   ```
   sudo systemctl restart nginx
   ```

10. Filestash is now installed and accessible via a web browser at http://your_domain_name.com/.

